 <p><center><a href="http://pub17.ezboard.com/ftheblackbag24069frm1" target="_self"><img src=http://phishstudios.50megs.com/phish.gif ></a></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ualucard1515.showPublicProfile?language=EN>alucard1515</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator <img src=http://contest.polykarbon.com/badge1.gif></span><br> <font color=#336699>(4/4/02 12:32:27 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1526.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.undeadart.com/forum/alucard.gif width=100 height=94></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Re:What makes a good battle??????</span><hr size=1> Well, now, wouldn't that all depend on the fight? Sure, if someone was fighting someone that would give them less trouble, one or two pages, or even panels, might be enough to cover it. But what about the epic final battles? Now, it may be hard to make it long without making it seem as if it's dragging out, but if it's done right, then you can get some really impressive stuff. And um... yes people can be equal, or at least fairly equally matched. Fights would be boring if someone always had a clear advantage over another.<br>
<br>
But I'm with Otakulad. For the most part, I like to see a fight when there's a reason for it. I'm not saying fights, if well done, aren't intersting to watch even if there's no real reason, but they are much more entertaining in my opinion if there's a reason for it. It just makes it seem all the more meaningful. <br>
<br>
And also, I don't like it when good and bad is so oversimplified. Most of the time the separation is so black and white, good versus bad. I like it better when there's at least a LITTLE crossover. The &quot;good&quot; guy might be fighting for a good cause, but at the same time he might also have some motivations of vengeance, or have something to gain. The &quot;bad&quot; guy might be fighting for something the hero doesn't agree with, but maybe he has good intentions, he's just going about it in the wrong way? I don't know, something like that, those are just examples. It makes the characters more than just flat and boring cliches. <p><table width=100% border=0>
